<font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="5"><b>How a bigot got the boot</b></font><p>
<font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">April 20, 2007 | Pages 8 and 9</font><p>

<font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">DAVE ZIRIN is a sportswriter and columnist for the <i>Nation </i>magazine. He is following up his first book <i>What's My Name, Fool? Sports and Resistance in the United States</i> with a second, soon to be published by Haymarket Books, Welcome to the Terrordome: The Pain, Politics and Promise of Sports. Here, he talks to <i>Socialist Worker </i>about Don Imus' firing.<p>
<p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="1">- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -</font></p>

<font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>IMUS APOLOGIZED for his comment about the Rutgers players, but it certainly wasn't the only racist slur to come out of his mouth, was it?</b><p>

NOT AT all. Imus likened his comments to a slip of the tongue, but history tells us otherwise.<p>
As Fairness and Accuracy in Reporting has documented, the "shlock jock" had a long and ugly history of using his radio program as a platform for prejudice. He called African-American journalist Gwen Ifill "a cleaning lady," <i>New York Times </i>sports reporter Bill Rhoden a "quota hire," and tennis player Amelie Mauresmo a "big lesbo."<p>
He told <i>60 Minutes </i>that he hired producer Bernard McGuirk for "n----r jokes." His co-host Sid Rosenberg described tennis player Venus Williams as an "animal" and referred to Palestinians as "stinking animals," saying, "They ought to drop the bomb right there, kill 'em all right now."<p>

